HOUSE BILL 1479
K3, P4, L6 6lr3624
By: Delegates Boafo, Charkoudian, Amprey, Bhandari, Fennell, A. Johnson,
Kaiser, Lehman, Terrasa, Turner, and White Holland
Introduced and read first time: February 13, 2026
Assigned to: Government, Labor, and Elections
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Labor and Employment – Minimum Wage – Increase
3 (Maryland Raise the Wage Act)
4 FOR the purpose of increasing the State minimum wage rate to a certain amount for certain
5 employers for certain calendar years; increasing, except under certain
6 circumstances, the State minimum wage rate in effect for certain periods of time
7 based on annual growth in a certain consumer price index, as determined by the
8 Commissioner of Labor and Industry; and generally relating to the payment of
9 wages.
10 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
11 Article – Labor and Employment
12 Section 3–413
13 Annotated Code of Maryland
14 (2025 Replacement Volume)
15 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
16 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
17 Article – Labor and Employment
18 3–413.
19 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
20 (2) “CONSUMER PRICE INDEX” MEANS THE CONSUMER PRICE INDEX
21 FOR ALL URBAN CONSUMERS FOR THE WASHINGTON–ARLINGTON–ALEXANDRIA,
22 DC–VA–MD–WV METROPOLITAN AREA OR A SUCCESSOR METROPOLITAN AREA
23 INDEX PUBLISHED BY THE FEDERAL BUREAU OF LABOR STATISTICS.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *hb1479*

2 HOUSE BILL 1479
1 (3) “Employer” includes a governmental unit.
2 [(3)] (4) “Small employer” means an employer that employs [14] 49 or
3 fewer employees.
4 (b) Except as provided in subsection (d) of this section and § 3–414 of this subtitle,
5 each employer shall pay:
6 (1) to each employee who is subject to both the federal Act and this subtitle,
7 at least the greater of:
8 (i) the minimum wage for that employee under the federal Act; or
9 (ii) the State minimum wage set under subsection (c) of this section;
10 and
11 (2) to each other employee who is subject to this subtitle, at least the
12 greater of:
13 (i) the highest minimum wage under the federal Act; or
14 (ii) the State minimum wage set under subsection (c) of this section.
15 (c) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, the State
16 minimum wage rate is:
17 (i) [for the 12–month period beginning January 1, 2023, $13.25 per
18 hour; and
19 (ii)] FOR THE 48–MONTH PERIOD beginning January 1, 2024,
20 $15.00 per hour;
21 (II) FOR THE 12–MONTH PERIOD BEGINNING JANUARY 1, 2028,
22 $18.00 PER HOUR; AND
23 (III) FOR EACH SUBSEQUENT 12–MONTH PERIOD BEGINNING
24 JANUARY 1, 2029, AND EACH JANUARY 1 THEREAFTER, THE RATE DETERMINED BY
25 THE COMMISSIONER UNDER PARAGRAPH (3)(II) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
26 (2) The State minimum wage rate for a small employer is:
27 (i) [for the 12–month period beginning January 1, 2023, $12.80 per
28 hour; and

HOUSE BILL 1479 3
1 (ii) beginning] FOR THE 60–MONTH PERIOD BEGINNING January
2 1, 2024, $15.00 per hour;
3 (II) FOR THE 12–MONTH PERIOD BEGINNING JANUARY 1, 2029,
4 $18.00 PER HOUR; AND
5 (III) FOR EACH SUBSEQUENT 12–MONTH PERIOD BEGINNING
6 JANUARY 1, 2030, AND EACH JANUARY 1 THEREAFTER, THE RATE DETERMINED BY
7 THE COMMISSIONER UNDER PARAGRAPH (3)(II) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
8 (3) (I) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBPARAGRAPH (III) OF THIS
9 PARAGRAPH AND SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (IV) OF THIS PARAGRAPH, THE
10 STATE MINIMUM WAGE RATE SHALL BE INCREASED BY THE AMOUNT, ROUNDED TO
11 THE NEAREST 5 CENTS, THAT EQUALS THE PRODUCT OF:
12 1. A. FOR THE PURPOSE OF DETERMINING THE WAGE
13 RATE IN EFFECT UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)(III) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE STATE
14 MINIMUM WAGE RATE IN EFFECT FOR THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 12–MONTH
15 PERIOD UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION; OR
16 B. FOR THE PURPOSE OF DETERMINING THE WAGE RATE
17 IN EFFECT UNDER PARAGRAPH (2)(III) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE STATE MINIMUM
18 WAGE RATE IN EFFECT FOR THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 12–MONTH PERIOD
19 UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION; AND
20 2. THE AVERAGE PERCENT GROWTH IN THE CONSUMER
21 PRICE INDEX FOR THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 12–MONTH PERIOD, AS
22 DETERMINED BY THE COMMISSIONER UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (II)1 OF THIS
23 PARAGRAPH.
24 (II) 1. SUBJECT TO SUBSUBPARAGRAPH 2 OF THIS
25 SUBPARAGRAPH, EACH SEPTEMBER 1, THE COMMISSIONER SHALL DETERMINE AND
26 ANNOUNCE:
27 A. THE AVERAGE PERCENT GROWTH, IF ANY, IN THE
28 CONSUMER PRICE INDEX BASED ON THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 12–MONTH
29 PERIOD FOR WHICH DATA ARE AVAILABLE ON MAY 1; AND
30 B. THE STATE MINIMUM WAGE RATE THAT WILL BE
31 EFFECTIVE FOR THE 12–MONTH PERIOD BEGINNING THE FOLLOWING JANUARY 1.

4 HOUSE BILL 1479
1 2. THE COMMISSIONER SHALL MAKE THE
2 ANNOUNCEMENT REQUIRED UNDER SUBSUBPARAGRAPH 1 OF THIS
3 SUBPARAGRAPH:
4 A. FOR THE STATE MINIMUM WAGE RATE THAT WILL BE
5 IN EFFECT UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)(III) OF THIS SUBSECTION, BEGINNING
6 SEPTEMBER 1, 2028; AND
7 B. FOR THE STATE MINIMUM WAGE RATE THAT WILL BE
8 IN EFFECT UNDER PARAGRAPH (2)(III) OF THIS SUBSECTION, BEGINNING
9 SEPTEMBER 1, 2029.
10 (III) IF THE COMMISSIONER DETERMINES THAT THERE IS A
11 DECLINE OR NO GROWTH IN THE CONSUMER PRICE INDEX, THE STATE MINIMUM
12 WAGE RATE SHALL REMAIN THE SAME AS THE RATE THAT WAS IN EFFECT FOR THE
13 IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 12–MONTH PERIOD.
14 (IV) 1. AN INCREASE IN THE MINIMUM WAGE RATE
15 DETERMINED BY THE COMMISSIONER UNDER THIS PARAGRAPH MAY NOT EXCEED
16 5% OF THE MINIMUM WAGE RATE IN EFFECT FOR THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING
17 12–MONTH PERIOD.
18 2. THE COMMISSIONER MAY NOT TEMPORARILY
19 SUSPEND AN INCREASE TO THE MINIMUM WAGE RATE REQUIRED UNDER THIS
20 SECTION FOR ANY REASON.
21 (d) An employer may pay an employee a wage that equals a rate of 85% of the
22 State minimum wage established under this section if the employee is under the age of 18
23 years.
24 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
25 October 1, 2026.

